{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d73e817c-e189-43a2-ac8a-f8c4314dbe6c","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n\n2. **Reproduce the crash.** macOS will write a core file to the configured path.\n\n3. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS also saves `.ips` / `.crash` logs in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the core dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   bt        # backtrace\n   thread list\n   ```\n\n5. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily disable System Integrity Protection or use `lldb` to attach and catch the crash live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app -- <args>\n   run\n   ```\n\n**Key notes for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, `createdump` isn't bundled. You rely on OS-level core dumps and `lldb` instead of `dotnet-dump`. The native symbols in NativeAOT binaries make `lldb` backtraces quite readable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dd381ab2-6a6a-4899-940d-812b9956d020","outputTokens":368,"requestId":"A0D8:35214E:983AA8:BAEB50:6A013759"},"id":"8c724552-1e1b-44f1-8f7c-925caaca47a0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:56:50.847Z","parentId":"5e88eda2-7def-41c9-ab31-a19331ec90f6"}
